Classifiying gastrointestinal diseases using a variety of models from simple sequential CNNs, to transferred-learning models using Xception, EfficentNet, and InceptionV3.¶

In this project, we hope to accurately classify a variety of colon-related diseases using medical images. We will be limited on computing power so the size of the models we can build from scratch will be quite small, later in the project, we get around this by utilising transferred learning and incorporating the architecture, and weights of much larger and much more sophisticated models.

We will create a simple shallow CNN as a baseline and iterate on this to maximize performance.

Data Description¶

The data we will be looking at contains images of colons with one of three possible conditions, and also healthy colons. The three condition cateogires, and healthy category are:

  • normal (healthy)
  • ulcerative colitis
  • polyps
  • esophagitis

The images were collected in 2017 by Wireless Capsule Endoscopy (WCE) to help with the early diagnosis of colon cancer. These images were later used to better understand the three gastrointestinal diseases mentioned above, and create methods for automatically detecting their presnece.

The images are already split into train/test/validation (53%/33%/14%). each dataset is made up of the four categories mentioned above. All categories are evenly sized (25% of each dataset for each category)

Loading in the data¶

Since we already have the data split into train, test, and validation sets we will simply create a separate object for each to start with.

Despite the images being roughly 531x633 pixels large we choose to re-size them to 128x128, the logic behind this is simple; firstly, our GPU runtime is limited, reducing the dimensionality of the images will reduce the total number of parameters, making computation significantly faster. Secondly, the images are of high-quality medical images of the colon; naturally, colons are rather diverse, as such using the full-sized version of the images could very easily lead to over-fitting due to the natural noise of the images, for example, natural differences in coloration, bumps, and grooves.

The hope is that by re-sizing the images we will still capture the major featural differences that differentiate between the 4 categories, but with less noise.

preparing the data for modeling¶

cache and prefetch¶

Since our datasets are not huge we can cache them, meaning our datasets are saved in memory, as opposed to being read from disk each time the data is called. This greatly saves time, especially for deep-learning tasks where you may read/write the same dataset several hundred times when training a single model.

We also use auto-tuned pre-fetch which parallelises pre-processing and model executing between successive batches.

In [ ]:
def cache_and_prefetch(tf_dataset):
  '''
  This function caches and prefetches the data in a TensorFlow dataset to improve the performance of the data pipeline.

  Args:
  tf_dataset: a TensorFlow Dataset object to cache and prefetch.

  Returns:
  The same TensorFlow Dataset object with caching and prefetching applied.
  '''

  tf_dataset.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
  return tf_dataset

Notice that the runtime of the below cell is 0 seconds; the datasets are not at this stage stored in memory. despite cacheing them here. Instead, when the first epoch is processed in our future model the data will be read once, and then held in memory between all succseive epochs.

In [ ]:
train_data = cache_and_prefetch(train_data)
validation_data = cache_and_prefetch(validation_data)

Baseline model¶

Our three datasets have been successfully loaded. It is now time to start thinking about creating a model; Before we design, and optimise our final model we will spend a little time developing a simple baseline model to compare against.

The Baseline will be a shallow CNN with no regularization.

Callbacks¶

Here we define three callbacks; the first is for early stopping if training loss doesn't decrease by more than a defined amount, over a defined number of consecutive epochs, training ends. This is simply to minimize the amount of redundant training.

Secondly, we define a callback to save weights during training, this isn't too useful for the baseline model since it only takes a minute or so to run, but our final model will presumably take a bit more time. saving weights during training allows us to get the best weights out if our program crashes or times out. We have it set to save off only the best weights based on validation accuracy, i.e if a given epoch has the highest validation accuracy the weights in that layer will be saved.

Thirdly, we define a custom callback that simply captures the time taken per epoch, this Epoch_Time is captured in the Callback.log() which can be accessed in the history object of the model. This means we can use it to create visualizations for training times.

In [ ]:
# custom callback for time per epoch
class EpochTime(keras.callbacks.Callback):
  def __init__(self,metric_name = "epoch_time"):
    self.__epoch_start = None
    self.__metric_name = metric_name
  def on_epoch_begin(self,epoch,logs=None):
    self.__epoch_start = tf.timestamp()
  def on_epoch_end(self,epoch,logs=None):
     logs[self.__metric_name] = tf.timestamp()-self.__epoch_start
In [ ]:
def earlystop(monitor="val_loss",min_delta=1e-4,patience=3):
  callback_earlystop = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
      monitor=monitor,
      min_delta=min_delta,
      patience=patience
  )
  return callback_earlystop

def checkpoints(filepath,monitor="val_accuracy"):
  callback_checkpoints = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
    filepath = filepath,
    monitor="val_accuracy",
    save_freq="epoch",
    save_weights_only=True,
    save_best_only=True
  )
  return callback_checkpoints

def eval_plots(history):
  """
    This function plots the training and validation loss and accuracy of a model.

    Parameters:
    history (keras.callbacks.History): the history object returned by the model fit function.

    Returns:
    None
  """
  history_dict = history.history

  loss = history_dict['loss']
  val_loss = history_dict['val_loss']

  accuracy=history_dict["accuracy"]
  val_accuracy = history_dict["val_accuracy"]

  epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)

  blue_dots = 'bo'
  solid_blue_line = 'b'

  red_dots = "ro"
  solid_red_line = "r"

  fig, (ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(2,1,figsize=(10,5),sharex=True)

  ax1.plot(epochs, loss, blue_dots, label = 'Training loss')
  ax1.plot(epochs, val_loss, solid_blue_line, label = 'Validation loss')
  ax1.set_title('Training and validation loss')
  ax1.set_ylabel('Loss')
  ax1.legend()

  ax2.plot(epochs, accuracy, red_dots, label = 'Training Accuracy')
  ax2.plot(epochs, val_accuracy, solid_red_line, label = 'Validation Accuracy')
  ax2.set_title('Training and validation Accuracy')
  ax2.set_xlabel('Epochs')
  ax2.set_ylabel('Accuracy')
  ax2.legend()

  plt.show()

# This code has been adapted from the DLWP example code.

Baseline model - results¶

Our baseline model is greatly overfitting to the training data, by the second epoch the training accuracy is already at 1 and the validation accuracy stays fixed at 0.735. This is to be expected, our model has a very small capacity, and no measures were taken to increase generalizability. This can be addressed by adding more layers, including dropout layers, and optimizing hyperparameters.

Data augmentation¶

A common method to reduce overfitting is to include a data augmentation layer, simply we apply a variety of random changes to our training images to create a more rich search space for our model to learn from, the changes must be realistic to ensure the extra information learned is transferable to un-seen, and un-augmented data.

Here we choose to include random vertical and horizontal flips, a change in image brightness, and cropping areas of 94x94 pixels. All of these changes should create a more rich search space, without creating any completely unrealistic images.

In [ ]:
augmentation_layer = keras.Sequential(
    [
     layers.RandomFlip("horizontal_and_vertical"),
     layers.RandomBrightness(0.3),
     layers.RandomCrop(height=94,
                       width=94,
                       seed=123)
    ]
)

example optimization code for a homemade inception model.¶

Again we won't run this but hopefully, it gets across the idea of what's possible with the Keras tuner! (we will be using it later for our transferred-learning models but not to this extent)

What we included¶

We have an inception model that is made up of three branches, but each of those three branches is made up of customizable components. The optimization algorithm will iterate through sets of parameters (defined using the hp methods in the below code) which will choose what values to set the different hyperparameters at, whether or not to include more or fewer layers, and what type of layers should be there. As an example; in Branch A we start with a single conv2D layer with an optimizable regularization parameter, this then feeds into between 0 and 4 layers, each of which can be a conv2D layer, a dropout layer, or a max-pooling layer. This could come up with some ridiculous combinations i.e 4 straight dropout layers. The hyperband optimization algorithm we choose to use will quickly remove these from the pool of possible models so we don't worry about that here. The same methodology is repeated for branches B and C, although we ensure to mix up the architecture enough so that each branch will hopefully capture different features of the feature-search space.

In [ ]:
## example optimisation code for an inception model.

# hyperparameter sets
def model_builder(hp):
    
  inputs = keras.Input(shape=(image_width,image_height,3))

  x = augmentation_layer(inputs)
  x= normalization_layer(x)
  


  # branch_a

  branch_a_L1 = hp.Float("L1_regularization",1e-5,1e-4)
  branch_a_L2 = hp.Float("L2_regularization",1e-5,1e-4)
  branch_a =layers.Conv2D(filters=32,
                kernel_size=hp.Choice("kernal_size",[3,5]),
                activation="relu",padding="same",
                kernel_regularizer=regularizers.L1L2(l1=branch_a_L1, 
  
                                                      l2=branch_a_L2))(x)
  # choose the number of optional layers to add to branch a                                                    
  for i in range(hp.Int("Branch_a_layers",0,4)):
    # choose what kind of layer to add
    for i in hp.Choice("branch_a_layer_type",["conv","pool","drop"]):
      if i=="conv":
        branch_a = layers.Conv2D(
            filters=32,
            activation="relu",padding="same"
        )(branch_a)
      if i =="pool":
       branch_a = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(branch_a)
      
      if i == "drop":
        branch_a = layers.Dropout(hp.Choice([0.2,0.3,0.4,0.5]))(branch_a)


  # branch_b
  # we want to ensure branch_b is sufficently differnt to branch_a so we will 
  # change the options we give it.
  
  branch_b = layers.Conv2D(filters=128,kernel_size=3)(x)
  branch_b = layers.Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=3)(x)
  # add or dont add a dropout layer.
  if hp.Boolean("branch_b_dropout"):
    branch_b = layers.Dropout(0.5)
  
  
  # branch_c

  branch_c_L1 = hp.Float("L1_regularization_branch_c",1e-5,1e-4)
  branch_c_L2 = hp.Float("L2_regularization_branch_c",1e-5,1e-4)
  
  #always include atleast this one layer
  branch_c =layers.Conv2D(filters=256,
                kernel_size=hp.Choice("Kernel_size_branc_c",[3,5]),
                activation="relu",padding="same",
                kernel_regularizer=regularizers.L1L2(l1=branch_c_L1, 
  
                                                      l2=branch_c_L2))(x)
  # choose the number of optinal layers to add to branch c                                                    
  for i in range(hp.Int("Branch_a_layers",0,2)):
    # choose what kind of layer to add
    for i in hp.Choice("branch_a_layer_type",["conv","pool","drop"]):
      if i=="conv":
        branch_c = layers.Conv2D(
            filters=64,
            activation="relu",padding="same"
        )(branch_c)

      if i =="pool":
       branch_c = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(branch_c)
      
      if i == "drop":
        branch_c = layers.Dropout(hp.Choice([0.2,0.3,0.4,0.5]))(branch_c)
 

  conc_branches = layers.Concatenate([branch_a,branch_b,branch_c])

  conc_branches = layers.Flatten()(x)
  outputs= layers.Dense(4,activation="softmax")(x)

  model_test = keras.Model(inputs,outputs)

  hp_learning_rate = hp.Float('learning_rate',1e-5,1e-3) 
  model_test.compile(keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=hp_learning_rate ), 
                  loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
                  metrics=["accuracy"])
  return model_test



tuner = kt.Hyperband(model_builder,
                     objective='val_accuracy',

Utilising Transfer learning¶

Transfer learning is the process of using pre-trained generalizable models on your specific tasks, this is possible for many deep-learning tasks where there is a similarity in feature space between the two domain problems. Computer vision-related tasks are included in this; many features learned in computer vision are very similar to those that would be seen in completely different tasks, for example; a large, complex neural network could be trained on cars but it would possibly be able to correctly classify jet-skis from trees without any additional training, why is this possible? Because several features learned from a car dataset will be similar to those seen in jet skis, but not in trees. For example; the vibrant colours of jet skis, the sharp angles, and the dark rounded seat may all be identified successfully by this transfer model.

These models are also trained on huge, feature-rich datasets, including this in our model will greatly improve the generalizability of the model.

For these reasons, we make use of several pre-trained models that have achieved state-of-the-art performance on a wide variety of computer vision tasks.

Transfer learning workflow.¶

Freezing pre-trained model weights¶

As previously mentioned, the pre-trained model has already been trained on a very large and very rich image dataset, for this reason, the layer weights have already been optimized for general computer vision tasks, and for this reason, we initially freeze the pre-trained model weights. If we didn't do this then the weights would get changed when we initially start fitting our model to our task-specific images.

Building a top-layer¶

Despite these pre-trained models being very powerful it is still important that we define a top layer. That is a few layers that do not have the pre-trained model's weights. This allows us to make task-specific adaptions that the transferred model may not necessarily be great at picking up.

Training the top-layer¶

As mentioned, the pre-trained model's weights are frozen, we can then train our model to optimize the top layer's weights for our task.

Fine-tuning the transferred-weights¶

Once our model has an optimized top layer that is specific to our task, we can train our model again with the transferred weights unfrozen, this will change the optimized "general" weights of the model and make them more task-specific. We can do this now, whereas before it may have been a bad idea since our model isn't starting from "scratch", again our top-layer is already optimized for our task.

Hyperparameter optimization¶

As was introduced before, for optimization we will make use of keras's implementation of the hyperband library. The main motivation for this is its speed since we are limited in computing power. Hyperband splits the parameters defined in our parameter space into brackets, these brackets then essentially "compete" against each other. To start, the algorithm will train each set of parameters on just 2 epochs, after all sets of parameters are trained the best-performing parameters are carried through to the next round of testing where they will be trained for 4 epochs, this repeats until one set of parameters is left.

This methodology ensures the worst-performing parameters are discarded early on, and only the best parameters are optimized using the full number of epochs.

defining a parameter search space¶

a parameter search space can be defined using a variety of hyperband methods such as:

  • hp.Choice: chooses a parameter from a list of parameters
  • hp.Boolean: set the value to either 0 or 1
  • hp.Float: set the value to a float value between a min and max

A full list of methods can be found here: https://keras.io/api/keras_tuner/hyperparameters/

Other useful utilities of hypertune¶

We can very quickly define a directory to store test results, this ensures if our program crashes, our runtime ends, or we simply re-run the notebook training progress is saved, and it won't re-run any tests that are already completed. we can also make use of tensorboards using the keras.callbacks.TensorBoard() callback, we can use this to visualize the tuning and get a better understanding of how different parameter combinations found in our search space perform.

In [ ]:
# hyperparameter sets
def model_builder(hp):
  """
    This function builds a Convolutional Neural Network (ConvNet) with the architecture specified and hyperparameters
    selected using Hyperparameter tuning.

    Parameters:
    hp (hyperopt.fmin.Trials): The hyperparameter tuning trials object returned by the Hyperparameter tuning library.

    Returns:
    model (keras.Model): A compiled Keras model with the specified architecture and hyperparameters.

  """
  # define parameter-space
  # NOTE: this parameter-space is in no way exhaustive, we may miss the optimal
  # solution but we are limited on computing power.
  # using quite a higher LR due to limited computing power - i.e limited epochs!
  
  hp_model_select = hp.Choice("model",values=[""])


 # Do not include the ImageNet classifier at the top.
 # build our task-specific top-layer
  inputs = keras.Input(shape=(image_width,image_height,3))

  x = Xception_augmentation_layer(inputs)
  x= layers.Rescaling(scale=1 / 127.5, offset=-1)(x) # need to scale to [-1,+1] rather than [0,1] for Xception model.

  # give the tuner three base-models to choose from.
  base_model = hp.Choice("base_model", ["Xception", "EfficentNet","InceptionV3"])
  if base_model == "Xception":
    x= base_model_Xception(x,training=False)
  if base_model == "EfficentNet":
    x = base_model_EfficentNet(x,training=False)
  if base_model == "InceptionV3":
    x= base_model_InceptionV3(x,training=False)

  # Add a pooling layer and dropout layer to help with generalizability.
  x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
  
  # Give the tuner the option to add between 0, and 2 Dense layers.
  for i in range(hp.Int("num_layers",0,2)):
    x = layers.Dense(hp.Choice('units', values=[256]))(x) # note here we only actually supply one choice.
  
  #test with and without a dropout layer.
  if hp.Boolean("dropout"):
    x = layers.Dropout(hp.Choice("Dropout",values=[0.5]))(x) #note here we only actually supply one choice.

  x= layers.Flatten()(x)
  outputs= layers.Dense(4,activation="softmax")(x)


  model_Xception=keras.Model(inputs=inputs,outputs=outputs)
  # test with a variety of learning rate
  # in reality we would use hp.Float here to take values between an upper
  # and lower limit, but again we only supply one value here.
  hp_learning_rate = hp.Choice('learning_rate', values=[1e-3]) 
  model_Xception.compile(keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=hp_learning_rate ), 
                  loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
                  metrics=["accuracy"])
  return model_Xception



tuner = kt.Hyperband(model_builder,
                     objective='val_accuracy',
                     max_epochs=15,
                     directory='/content/drive/MyDrive/CW2_models/Xception_model',
                     overwrite=True,
                     executions_per_trial=1, # only run each trial once due to computation limitations
                     project_name='Colon_classifcation'
                    )

Tensorboards Tensorflow has a cool extension that utilizes the keras.callbacks.TensorBoard() function we passed as a callback in our tuner trials. It shows an in-line interactive dashboard that outlines several interesting features of the trials, for example, accuracy and loss graphs for all trials all in the same place, and hyperparameter graphs that let you see how choosing different parameters lead to different results. One of these graphs is shown below. Note: This is not the full graph! We chose to filter out InceceptionV3 and EfficentNet models for clarity. This is a parallel feature graph, each line represents a model and each vertical line represents a parameter choice or performance metric. We can see some correlation between certain parameter choices and model performance. As an example, For our Xception models the dropout layer was only excluded once (model highlighted in green)and it lead to an incredibly small training_loss value, Clearly this leads to more overfitting than all the other iterations that included the dropout layer! This would also suggest our model requires regularization. If we had access to more GPU power we would test different values for the dropout layer parameter, including more dropout layers, and test different float values for L1 and L2 regularization in our Dense layers

def get_best_epoch(history):
  
  lowest_val_loss = min(history.history["val_loss"])

  best_epoch = history.history["val_loss"].index(lowest_val_loss)
  print(f"The best Epoch for this model is: {best_epoch} with a val_loss of: {lowest_val_loss}")
  return best_epoch

Evaluating our models.¶

Now we have all of our models we can finally evaluate them on our test data.

We will make use of Sklearn's classifcation_report function which shows class-specific metrics and an overall F1 score. F1-scores encapsulate the distribution of predictions across the classes, so we can get a better understanding of how our models perform across all classes rather than a flat overall accuracy which could do good at predicting certain classes, but be terrible at others.

In [ ]:
def evaluate_model(model,test_data):
  y_pred = []
  y_true = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_data], axis=0)
  
  preds=model.predict(test_data)

  for i, p in enumerate(preds):
  # for each prediction choose the highest probability one.
        pred_index=np.argmax(p)
        y_pred.append(pred_index)
  
  print(classification_report(y_true,y_pred))
  return y_pred, y_true

Conclusion¶

As is expected, the final model that used Transfer-learning and was optimized using the keras.tuner package greatly outperformed the other models, seeing an f1-score of 0.92, 0.18 points higher than the baseline model.

Interestingly our attempts at optimizing our simple CNN failed, the baseline model outperformed both iterations that introduced data augmentation and regularization. I believe this is because we were basing success purely on our loss metric. We could see that the baseline model very rapidly fit the training data, and fit somewhat poorly to the validation data, our conclusion from this was that the model is picking up abstract features of the training data and overfitting to it, the natural solution to this is introducing regularization. In reality, I don't think overfitting was the issue. If we look at class-specific accuracies our baseline model performed rather well in 3 of the 4 classes, but 0 predictions were made in the 4th class. By regularizing we decreased the generalizability for the classes the model was good at predicting, and it didnt help with the 4th class at all! So in the end it worked against us. This could have been prevented by looking at f1-scores throughout rather than right at the end. This goes to show that accuracy alone should not be used when training models.

Lessons learned¶

If we had known about the issue of 0 precision and 0 recall in class 1 earlier, we would have changed our approach and focused on improving these metrics for class 1. The features that separated this class from the others are seemingly harder, or more complex to learn. Rather than simplifying and regularizing, we should have increased the complexity of our model by adding more capacity in the hopes that these more abstract ideas could be captured.

Visualising our final model¶

Let's delve a little deeper into our final model and try to understand how it succeeds in classifying different colons.

To start we visualize the channels in our model, due to the size of the Xception architecture we won't be able to visualize them all, we choose to look at the first 8 channels of a sub-set of layers. We will do this for an un-seen image belonging to each of the 4 classes so we can get a clear understanding of the difference between classes.

To do this we need to first identify and extract all convolutional layers from our model, these all exist within the Xception layer. Once we have all of the layers that we can visualize we will create a new model that has these layers as the output.

layer_outputs = []
layer_names = []

# need to get the convnet layers from the model.
for outer_layer in final_model_optimised.layers:
  # only convnet layers are within the xception architecutre, so we 
  # find the xception layer and then look at the layers nested in there.
  if "xception" in outer_layer.name: 
     # The xception layer defines its own input, so we need to save this off
     # to be used in defining our model. 
      Xception_input = outer_layer.input

      for inner_layer in outer_layer.layers:
        #if we have a convnet layer then append it to our layer list.
          if "conv" not in inner_layer.name:
            continue
          layer_outputs.append(inner_layer.output)
          # save off the names for the visualisations.
          layer_names.append(inner_layer.name)

# define our activation model and output the convnet layers.
activation_model = keras.Model(inputs=[final_model_optimised.input,
                                     Xception_input],
                               outputs=layer_outputs)

def get_activation_grids(layer_names,activations):
    # The base of this function is from Deep learning with Python Edition 2, page 265
  '''
    Returns a list of matrices where each matrix represents the output of an activation layer.
    
    Arguments:
    layer_names -- a list of strings representing the names of the activation layers.
    activations -- a list of tensors representing the outputs of the activation layers.
    
    Returns:
    display_grids_all -- a list of matrices, each matrix represents the output of an activation layer.
    layer_name -- a string representing the name of the last activation layer processed.
  '''

  display_grids_all = []
  images_per_row = 4
  for layer_name, layer_activation in zip(layer_names, activations):
      n_features = 8
      size = layer_activation.shape[1]
      n_cols = n_features // images_per_row
      display_grid = np.zeros((size * n_cols, images_per_row * size))
      for col in range(n_cols):
          for row in range(images_per_row):
            channel_image = layer_activation[0,
            :, :,
            col * images_per_row + row]
            channel_image -= channel_image.mean()
            channel_image /= channel_image.std()
            channel_image *= 64
            channel_image += 128
            channel_image = np.clip(channel_image, 0, 255).astype('uint8')
            display_grid[col * size : (col + 1) * size,
            row * size : (row + 1) * size] = channel_image
    
      display_grids_all.append(display_grid)
      
  return display_grids_all, layer_name

Analysing the activation layer outputs¶

The representation of our 4 classes is quite significantly different in most cases, especially between classes 0, 2, and 3. By the time you get a couple of layers down the outputs are picking up on completely different areas of the images. Interestingly, class_1 activation outputs seem to be keeping track of much higher-level features than the others which could explain why this class had the lowest f1-score.
